{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492856"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:47:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1170"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1170"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.07,0.78,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69180"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1170"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1170"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54637"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"9098"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9100"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11248"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69180"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department with a 4-hour history of increasing, generalised abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. The pain is constant and she has never experienced anything like this before. She has a medical history of atrial fibrillation. Her medications include warfarin. On examination, her pulse rate is 115/min and irregular, blood pressure 105/70 mmHg, and temperature is 37.2\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals widespread abdominal tenderness and decreased bowel sounds. Serum lactate and amylase are elevated while serum lipase is normal. A plain radiograph shows is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathological process?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perforated diverticulitis","Necrotising pancreatitis","Retroperitoneal haemorrhage","Mesenteric ischaemia","Perforated appendicitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the clinical picture could have a number of explanations, the observation of gas in the portal venous system (Image) is highly suggestive of a diagnosis of acute \u003Cstrong\u003Emesenteric ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (AMI). With today\u0027s high definition imaging systems (CT, MRI), the finding of small volumes of gas in the portal venous system is a relatively common finding - and often the underlying problem is treatable. The usual pre-disposing factors are mucosal damage, bowel distension, and sepsis. To be visible on a plain abdominal radiograph implies a large volume of gas and an aggressive underlying pathology. When seen in conjunction with mesenteric ischaemia, the presence of that volume of portal venous gas usually means advanced disease and a fatal outcome. Any form of intra-abdominal sepsis can lead to gas-forming organisms entering the portal venous system, however, in most conditions, the volumes of gas are usually small and only detected on CT imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the volume of gas is such that it can be seen on a plain abdominal radiograph, the most common explanation for this would be bowel wall necrosis secondary to AMI. AMI presents with sudden-onset abdominal pain which is out of proportion to the examination findings. The common risk factors for AMI are atherosclerosis, embolic phenomenon (eg, atrial fibrillation), and hypercoagulable disorders. Laboratory findings may reveal leukocytosis, elevated amylase, and anion-gap metabolic acidosis (due to increased levels of lactate).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with fever and left lower quadrant pain with or without hematochezia. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents with fever and right lower quadrant pain. \u003Cstrong\u003EPerforation\u003C/strong\u003E associated with either diverticulitis or appendicitis would present with abdominal guarding and rebound tenderness. Plain abdominal X-ray would show air under the diaphragm instead of portal venous gas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENecrotising pancreatitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a complication of acute pancreatitis which presents with abdominal pain that radiates to the back. Elevation in serum lipase is both sensitive and specific for pancreatitis. This patient\u0027s serum lipase is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpontaneous\u003Cstrong\u003E retroperitoneal haemorrhage \u003C/strong\u003Ecan occur in patients on anticoagulation. It may present with abdominal, flank, or back pain. Patients are usually haemodynamically unstable. However, elevated amylase and portal venous gas on imaging are unlikely to be seen in such patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe, generalised abdominal pain with guarding and radiological evidence of gas in the portal venous system equates to a diagnosis of mesenteric ischaemia."],"references":["Karkkainen JM. Acute mesenteric ischemia: A challenge for the acute care surgeon. Scand J Surg 2021;110:150\u201358. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33866891/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54637"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1170"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20582"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20583"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20582"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/74Ebs48RAqhdNTrqPqiiuLojHwREat.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/74Ebs48RAqhdNTrqPqiiuLojHwREat.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":338,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20583"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rsR9bDZFIY3vXHAoMTVEy8lXbwE5mh.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rsR9bDZFIY3vXHAoMTVEy8lXbwE5mh.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":338,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54637"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T11:29:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T11:29:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1170"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69180"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.